City Journal hit^ the nail\non the head in saying that opposition\nto fie Payne tariff law Is mainly a\nstate of mind, and an uncomfortable\nstate of mind, at that.\nSenator Aldrich is quoted as saying,\n\"Kansas is a great state, but there\nare more people in it with no sense\nat all than in any other state.\" \"'Tis\ntrue, 'tis pity and pity 'tis 'tis true.\"\nDave Palmer made a fine run for\nrailroad commissioner. Incidentally,\nit may be observed, some especially\ngood work was done in his behalf.\u2014\nCedar Rapids Gazette.\nSure, Mike! That's what counts.\nThe regular Republicans of Wiscon\nsin have the right idea and have\nformulated it aright: \"'We are against\nmen who are Republicans for office\nand Democrats in office.\" That is\nsound doctrine and good polltlea'\nsense.\nThey are getting quite apprehensive\ndown in St. Louis. A writer in the\n.Globe-Democrat, for instance, antici\npates that, in the year 1811\nvthe\norder\nof bacon and eggs will appear on the\ntable a, two eggs and a photograph\nof the bacon. Ought to be mighty\nthankful for the eggs.\n^Colonel Brookhart is quoted bv the\nWashington Press as saying- \"i am\nfor Charley Kennedy and further\nmore he is going to be elected.\" The\ndeclaration attests his Republicanism\nand Is highly creditable in every way\nto the late candidate for congression\nal honors.\nEighty-five large passenger locomo\ntives, to cost approximately $1,125,000,\nhave been ordered by the Harriman\nroads from the Baldwin locomotive\nworks in Philadelphia.- Deliveries will\nbe made in October, November and\nDecember. This is one of the largest\norders given by any railroad since the\nfinancial depression of 1907-8.\nMr. Charles Grille, Republican nom-\nS5.E rss? s,cr \u00bb\u2022*\u2022?'the\nGrant Club in Des Moinea art\u2122\nI\nthe abolition of the nipreme court so If^'if68\nfar as its power to review legislation hal frr^nn^h\nis concerned. He wants all the enM\ninterference by the courts. AIr Grilk\ngeography. This is Iowa not Okla\njoice with him and heartily congratu\nlate him on the splendid result.\nThe faculty committee of the state\neducational board of control has start\ned a canvass for a president to suc\nceed Dr. Storms at Ames college. It\nis stated that an Iowa man will be\nelected. Either Professor Curtiss or\nProfessor Holden, is thought to have\nthe best chance.\nTHE RAILROAD SITUATION.\nOne billion dollars will be needed\nby the railroads of the United States\nfor extensions and improvements\nwithin the next twelve months, accord\ning to the most conservative esti\nmates. Unless rates are advanced to\na point that will permit a material in\ncrease in net earnings it will not be\npossible to raise so great a sum.\nWithout the improvements the rail\nroads cannot handle any marked in\ncrease in traffic and the lack of\ntransportation facilities will reader\nimpossible any return of prosperity.\nThis is the rate situation as summed\nup by a railway financial officer.\nIn 1908, the total capital of the rail\nroads of the United States was\n$17,234,88^,215, as compared with\n$11,585,069,036 in 1898, an increase of\n$6,649,817,179, or an average of $564,\n981,717 per year. But the annual In\ncrease was most rapid in the closing\nyears of the period, being $1,030,349,\n026 in 190C, $907,864,112 in 1907 and\n$733,473,146 in the dull year of 1908.\nA study of financial publications\nemphasizes the increasing difficulty of\nraising money for railroad uses. Rail\nroad bonds which yielded interest at\nthe average rate of 4.97 per cent in\n1885 and 4.21 per cent in 1898 gave\nonly an average return of 3.88 per cent\nIn 1908. The outlook for the stock\nholder is even more discouraging, for\nthe ton mile freight rate which was\n.977 in 1888 had shrunk to .758 in 1898\nand to .765 in 1908. The average rate\nERRORS IN SPELLING.\nProf. G. M. Whipple, of Cornell\nuniversity, has given close attention\nto the spelling of students who have\ncontributed essays upon themes as\nsigned them and so general has poor\nspelling manifested itself that he has\nbeen led to Issue a suppositious letter\nfrom a student to a relative. In fifty\neight papers the professor discovered\n160 such mistakes, each of which was\nmade several times by the same stu\ndent or once by several students. They\noccurred after the papers had been re\nturned to the students for revision,\nwith a special demand for correction\no\u00a3 orthography, and in no case have\nerrors been included that were of a\ncertatuty mere slips of the pen. The\nillustration devised by the professor\nfollows\n\"Dear Aunt: Today I received my\ndiploma and now, thank fortun, I am\neducated. I have not intirely detir\nmined my carere. Wheatehr I shall\nfinaly earn my livlihood by going into\nthe soliciting business as my une'e's\npardoner will dipind on\n1\nhas evidently become confused in his A\nhoma. He would do well to correct1 'T\nFour insurgent speeches were made I J'\nwhich Swedesburg is located ami it rses\nJority. Mr. A. j. Anderson was twit-! [^v ar?\nted on being the only regular Repub\nlican left in the whole surrounding\ncountry. The result Is thus told in\nthe editorial ccflurnns of the Burling\nton Hawk-Eye:\nMr. Anderson did :iot, however, loss\nheart. On the contrary he went to\nwork and set others to work. When\nIf I.^u8 ,were counted the \"progres\nsives had forty-one and the stard\npatteis 128. It was great victory\nfo: Mr. Anderson and his friends re-\nper passenger per mile dwindled from there was a general decline until Aug\n2.246 in 1888 to 1.994 in 1898 and 1.950 I ust, 1908. Beginning with September,\ncents in 1908. 11908, there has been a monthly in\ncrease without a break up to March,\nbi3\nperfer-\nences. At any rate, labrous and hu\nmuliating manuel pursuits are fur\ntherest from my Intentions, as I ami\nconcious already that the university\ninvironment has prooved particularly\nvaluable to me in evry way. My in\ntellegual equlppement lias been ad\nvanced harmonously by immetatlon\nof the best sholars my vocabular has\nbeen strengthened suberstitions all\nmost as bad as those of the heathen\nhave been analised and prooved incor\nect to me mv lnaetiative has beea or\nroused and intencifled socially I am\nwell acquiped, and, Incidentily the\nrough eges I used to show have been\neliminated from tbe pratice work in\nthe labratories of physsics aod chem\nistry where persistance, courtsy, cour\naglousness and similar qualities are\ndefinately emphazed and the knowl\nedge I have received from the leclurs\nand disscussions of my professors in\nbonay, rhitoric. mathmatics, phisiolo\ngy, ect., should be a source of ines\ntimable benefit to me from whatever\nangel it is regarded.\"\nIt is no new thing that Professor\nWhipple has thus brought to public\nattention. The press and the business some impractical and a nuisance. V*\nworld have complained for years that\nthe schools are falling far short of\ntheir opportunity and their duty in\nthis Important matter. The poor spell-\ncording to th\u00a9 estimates of the Uni-\ndepa,Jtment\nof\ntbG\ncou.ntry\n1f^00worth\nactments of the legislatures and oi! T' \u00b0f *205-220-000- Only six'ther.\"\ncongress to go into effeT^tUfanv\n1\niTj T**\n1,Te\ntS Zt^\nBt\u00b0Ck\n\u00b0f\nto,re\u00bb\n1 00()\naH\nVal\"e\nexceeds tne\neS\na,\u00b0ne\nln\ntes are\nKansas'\nhis latitude and longitude before his \u2022\u00a3rSe*8 nearly 45 per cent\nDemocratic opponent takes advantage stock value of the\nor bis lapse of commonZme ST\"'' 'helr\nIUInois-\nIowa-\nTexas, Mis-\nNebraska\nand Ohio.\nas compared with $5,138,480,000\nmi,lch\nln\nhorses In\nwas heralded far and wide that the ^OS.19 per head. This is an\nprecinct would go against Taft, Car- \u00abiorK\nroll and Keimedv by a sweeping ma I\n^\"ws- cattle.\n\u00bb5\nS'Rthe nnit^/iT?\nBwine.\nin the township in Henry county in v, and mules. There are 21,040,000 secured some votes for Carroll, and\nth* ,t ,g\ncountry,\nof an average\nva!ue\nper\nhead-\nHorses are\nin New Jersey, where\nworth $1.34 each, and the\nJf,rSlV\nWW\u00b0\ncheapest In New Mexico, at $47.\nThe United States and Russia have\n_Vv\nas the United States, Argentina la\nthird on the list with 8,000,000 head.\nAsiatic Russia fourth with about 7,\n000,000 and Germany next with 4 000'\u2022\n000.\nThe second horse state is Iowa\nwhich has 1,447,000 head, valued at\n$120 each, a total of $173,640,000. Tex\nas probably to the surprise of most\npeople, is eighth on the list, being\npassed by the two states mentioned,\nand by Kansas, Ohio, Nebraska, Mis\nsouri and Indiana, although the Lone\nStar state has more horses than any\nof these seven states except Iowa and\nIllinois. Texas has 1,369,000 horses,\nbut they are worth only $73 each, a\ntotal of $99,937,000. Kansas has 1,187,\n000, valued at $127,00J,000, or $107\neach Ohio has only 977,000 head, but\nthey are worth $126,003,000, or $129\neach. Nebraska has 1,045,000 head\nworth $112,860,000, or $108 each. Mis\nsouri has 1,005,000 horses, which at\n$103 each are worth $103,515,00v. In\ndiana has 847,000 head, which at $122\neiich are worth $103,334,000.\nfollowing Texas in the copulation\nof horses come Michigan, New York,\nMinnesota, Pennsylvania, North Da\nkota, Wisconsin, Oklahoma, South Da\nkota, California, Kentucky and Ten\nnessee. These nineteen states have\nhorses valued at $l,826,t38,000, or 80\nper cent of the total for the country.\nANALYSIS OF PRICES.\nA report recently published by the\nbureau of labor of the department of\ncommerce and labor makes some very\ninteresting developments as to the\nsteady increase of the wholesale\nprice of 257 commodities which enter\ninto the everyday life of our people.\nThe figures cover a period of\ntwenty years, 189Q to 1909, inclus\nive.\nAccording to the report the general\nadvance has been 3 per cent for 1909\nover 1908, yet 1909 was 2.3 per cent\nlower than 1907. That is to say that\n1909 did not bring the wholesale\nprice of commodities back to where\nthey were before the panic of 1907.\nThe present year, however, will send\nIt above that mark.\nThe highest point reached in 1907\nwas in October, from which month\n1910. Wholesale prices in March, 1910,\nwere higher than at any time in the\npreceding twenty years, being 7.5 per\ncent higher than in March, 1909 10.2\nper cent higher than in August, 1908\n21.1 per cent higher than the average\nyearly prices of 1900, 49.2 per cent\nhigher than the average yearly price\nof 1897, and 33.8 per cent higher than\nthe average price for the ten years\n1890 to 1899.\nOf the 257 articles for which the\nwholesale prices were obtained, 125\nshowed an increase in the average\nprice for 1909 as compared with 1908.\nThinty-one showed no change and 101\nshowed a decrease.\nQ,f,the nine groups under which the\ncommodities are classified, six showed\nan increase in price in 1909 as com\npared with 1908, the largest percent\nage of increase being in farm prod\nucts, namely, 15.0 per cent. Lumber\nand building materials Increased 4.0\nper cent food, etc., 3.4 per cent\ncloths and clothing, 2.3 per cent and\ndrugs and chemicals, 1.8 per cent,\nwhile the miscellaneous group in\ncreased 5.0 per cent. The three groups\nin which the wholesale prices de\ncreased were house furnishing goods,\n2.0 per cent fuel and lighting, 1.1 per\ncent, and metals and implements, ,0-5\nper cent.\nThe average wholesale price of raw\ncommodities for 1909 was 9.0 peT cent\nhigher than in 1908, while in March,\n1910, it was 15.5 per cent higher than\nthe average for 1908 and 5.9 per cent\nhigher than the average for 1909. The\naverage wholesale price of manufac\ntured commodities for 1909 was 1.4\nper cent higher than for 1908, and in\nMarch, 1910, it was 7.2 per cent higher\nthan the average for 1908 and 5.7 per\ncent higher than the average for 1909\nthe March, 1910, price also showed an\nincrease of 1.0 per cent over January,\n1910, and of 0.8 per cent over Febru\nary, 1910.\nNOTES AND COMMENT.\nThe Ames Times is convinced that\nthe present primary law is bungle-\nThe St. Louis Globe-Democrat ob\nserves that one trouble of the Iowa\n[senators is that no private soldiers\nng of many of the common school apply to Join the army of insurgency.\ngraduates is a serious reflection upon\nour educational system. The Omaha Bee tells Nicaragua\nI .that, it would do well to heed Uncle\nHE LEADING HORSE STATES, Sam's warning of \"Hands off,\" before\nost people will be surprised to it gives provocation to say \"Hands\nknow that Illinois is the first horse up.\"\nstate in the Union, and not Texas, or\nThe past should be forgotten,\"\nsays the Coon Rapids Enterprise, \"and\nBoth\nagriculture an efTort made to get together, num\n\"\"nois factions and the party have too much\n$125 each, at stake to carry tbe fight any fur-\nThe Marshalltown Times-Republican\nanticipates that if congress holds on\nuntil July 15 Chautauqua audiences\nare likely to hear considerably more\nabout \"mother, liome and heaven\"\nthan of politics.\n\"Undoubtedly,\" concedes the Sioux\njCity Journal, \"the second term issue\nDQt lmprobable tfaat thJ\nmade by the senators secured some\nvotes for Garst.\"\nAn Albia boy who had been\nclothed with his father's cast-off ward\nrobe was one day found crying behind\nthe barn. \"Pa's gone and shaved hie\nabout one-hah the horses of the world, face clean,\" he exlalned \"and I sun-\nthe 8ame nUIDber P0se rH have t0 wear them red\nkers now,\"\nfiuuv auu auctvtfll IIIH\nwhi!-\nr\u201e rJs\n\"If Senator Cummins intends to be\nPresident,'' says the Dubuque Times\nJournal, \"he will have to make his\nfight against the renomination of\nPresident. Taft instead of waiting un-\nTHE DAILY GATE CITY]\ntil 1916, when the senator\nsixty-six years old.\"\nwill be\n\"Iowa's message to Taft,\" remarks\nthe Iowa City Republican, \"will be\none of confidence, of faith in the man,\na man who is trying to do what is\nhonest and right for the welfare of\nthe whole nation. That is one of the\nresults of the primary of last week?\"\nNew York and Brooklyn educators\nare said to intend going to Ohio this\nsummer to see Mrs. Catherine Estill\nof Ohio Northern University at Ada.\nShe has fed the students for twenty\nyears at ten. cents a meal. She gives\nthem things they like to eat and\nthings that they can afford to buy,\nand the easterners want to find out\nhow she does it.\n\"Chancellor Day Is ia wrong when\nhe denounces the automobile and its\ngeneral use,\" says the Cedar Rapids\nGazette. \"He is right, however, in de\nnouncing the abuse of the auto the\nextravagance which leads people to\ncultivate a\u00bb automobile appetite and\nsatisfy It when there is nothing but\na wheelbarrow income with which to\ndo the satisfying.\"\nMR. DAUGHERTY CORRECTS IN\nTERVIEW.\nActual Conditions at Keokuk During\nOld Steamboat Days.\nTo the Editor of Tne Gate City:\nI read with great interest the illus\ntrated historical write-up in Sunday's\nChicago Tribune of Keokuk's great\nwater power project by their corres\npondent, Hollis W. Field. But with\nall due deference to the gentleman\nI must take exceptions to his report\nof our brief interview wherein he\nreports me as stating that \"I have\nseen a thousand steamboats tied up\nat the Keokuk docks.\" This .exag\ngerated error must have crept in by\na mistake of the proof reader, by\nadding too many ciphers.\nWhat I did say was substantially\nthis: that I had seen over a dozen\nsmall steamers tied up along the shore\nof our levee receiving and discharg\ning freight for points on the Des\nMoines river between Keokuk and\nDes Moines and in very high water\non up to Ft. Dodge, and in addition\nto this fleet of steamers plying the\nDes Moines river prior to the war of\nthe rebellion was a double daily line\nof palatial steamers to St. Louis and\nnearly a double daily line of steam\ners from St.,Louis to St. Paul in ad\ndition to many tramp steamers from\nthe Ohio river, for the upper Missis\nsippi river to St. Paul, and in low wa\nter all these boats for the upper Mis\nsissippi would have to spend days at\nthe Keokuk wharf in transhipping\ntheir cargoes on to flats and barges\nto be towed with horses to Montrose,\nand the steamboats when stripped of\nevery article movable, would follow\non up over the rapidj and reload at\nMontrose, and in returning from\nGalena and St. Paul loaded down to\nthte guards with pig lead, grain, etc.,\nthese steamers would be compelled\nto litiload at Montrose and have their\ncargoes floated down over the rapids\nto Keokuk, the steamer then follow\ning oVer the rapids to again to be re\nloaded at Keokuk, and in addition we\nhad several daily short lines of steam\ners plying to Keokuk, viz: The Keo\nkuk and Qulncy and the Keokuk and\nDavenport packets, and a Warsaw\nboat, and at times a sma.l boat to\nMontrose and Nauvoo. All these\nsteamers plying to Keokuk made our\nlevee front lively then, and I predict\ned that when our channel in the Mis\nsissippl was assured in low water a\nsix foot stage between St. Louis and\nSt. Paul, and our dam and enlarged\nlock was completed, so as te take in\na tow boat and a large.tow of barges,\nwithout having to double trip, and\nthe Panama canal completed, our old\ntime river boom of early days would\nbe far eclipsed.\nJ. F. DAUGHERTY.\nGuessing Again.\nKewanee Star-Courier: \"Roose\nvelt to Head New Party,\" is the head\nabove a dispatch from Washington,\nprominently displayed on the first\npage of one of today's Chicago papers.\nWithout reading it you can safely set\nthis article down as fabricated* matter\nsent out during the Sunday night lull\nof news, at Washington, when the cor\nrespondents are put to their wits ends\nto get up something lively for the\nMon4ay papers. It is a difficult and\nwell nigh impossible matter to pre\ndict what Mr. Roosevelt will do and\nwill not do, but certainly no one can\nseriously think that it Is the organiza\ntion of a new party, which is engaging\nhis interest.\nCongressman Kennedy.\nBurlington Saturday Evening Post:\nThe strong vote for Congressman Ken\nnedy In this district at Tuesday's pri\nmary is a public testimonial to the\nworth and service .of a deserving man.\nIf we read the interpretation correct\nly, this tesamonial is offered by the\nvoters in the feeling that it ihas been\nwell earned by Mr Kennedy, whose\nthoughtful, well-considered and suc\ncessful service for four years past\nhas touched every neighborhood, in the\nseven counties. And whatever may\nbe the strength and humor of insur\ngent sentiment in other districts in\nthe state there need be no doubt of\nthe fact that Mr. Kennedy will receive\nthe same overwhelming endorsement\nin November that was given him in\nJune, His work for the whole dis\ntrict has created a sentiment so favor\nable to him and so strong that at this\ntime bis re-electioij is clearly fore\nseen. Mr. Kennedy is not a politician\nand knows next to nothing about the\nclever side of political manipulation.\nHe is a working man, eelf-educated,\nambitious to excel in actual perform\nance and merit, but without appetite\nor cane for honors not fairly and ful\nly earned. He is the most diligent\nworker in either house of congress\nand he does the ikind of work that\ntells of itself. He is the last man\nin congress to advertise anything that\nhe has done for his district or for any\none in It. Congressman Kennedy is\nstill a young man, has a good mind\" in\na good body, and will continue to\nmake progress in all-around growth\nin personal force and in reputation as\nlong as he chooses to remain in public\nlife.\nThe Return of \"Teddy.\"\nThe Black Diamond: Colonel\nRoosevelt is now on the water bound\nhome. Barring the possibility of an\nunfortunate encounter with a lion or\na rhinoceros, that was expected. So\nit is not an unusual thing, therefore,\nit is not news, yet the newspapers\nmake a terrible fuss about It. We are\nwondering why.\nMr. Roosevelt made a number of\nspeeches abroad. There Is nothing\nunusual about that, because Teddy\nmakes speeches and upon the slight\nest provocation. Since it is not un\nusual, it is not news, et the news\npapers have been much concerned\nabout it. Again we wonder why.\nThen Colonel Roosevelt was re\nceived by royalty. There is nothing\nunusual about that, therefore It is not\nnews, because the royalty of Europe\nare principally the chartered enter\ntainers for the nation kings are in\nthe habit of receiving people, even\npretty young girls whose fathers are\nrich. It can't be that such a thing:\nhas given us any larger opinion of\nColonel Roosevelt, because we are a\ndemocratic people and don't care\nmuch for kings anyway. Why do the\nnewspapers rave over it?\nIt may be that a lot of people have\nthe notion that because Roosevelt\nstarted something and kept it up for\nseven years, he is the only man who\ncan do things. Now we haven't a\nthing against Roosevelt he filled his\njob and he filled it well. But we\nknow the difference between preach\ning and doing. In the latter respect,\nwe have pretty large and very whole\nsome respect for the gentleman now\nin the white house. He may talk a\nlot, but he goes home and works af\nter the talking is over. We are some\nwhat inclined to believe that if the\nnewspapers would give to Taft, the\nworker, the same encouragement they\ngave to Roosevelt, the preacher, we\nwould be so busy getting things done\nwe would not have time to speculate\non who would be nominated in 1911.\nA\nSALEM.\nAfter having completed her four\nscore and three years of life, Mrs.\nHarriet Lester passed away at 8:30\no'clock Wednesday evening, June 8,\n1910. Harriet White was born in\nMansfield, Vermont, June 11, 1827.\nAt the age of three years she, with her\nparents, Hoser and Gratia White\nmoved to Stanstead, Canada, and spent\nher girlhood days In that vicinity.\nWhen she was nineteen years of age\nshe came with her parents to Iowa.\nOne month was consumed in the trip\nto Chicago, it being made by canal\nand steamboat. The remainder of the\njourney was made overland. The\nfamily arrived at Ft. Madison July 5,\n1846. and from there they went to\nWest Point. She was one of a family\nof nin,e children, one of whom, Edwin\nWhite, of dreensburg, Indiana, sur\nvives her. October 17, 1848, at West\nPoint, sbe was united in marriage to\nAntrim I^ester and with her husband\nlocated at Salem, Iowa, the follow\ning December. To this union was\nborn eight children, six of whom sur\nTive her. Mrs. Ida L. Johnson, of\nIowa City, Horace of Cashmere, Wash\nington, Mrs. Llllie L. Johnson of Green\nCastle, Missouri, George, Albert and\nBertha, who resided with and tender\nly cared for their mother. The hus\nband, a son, Marval, and a daughter,\nMrs. Jennie L. Haskett, preceeded\nher in death. She leaves four grand\nchildren, Mrs. Hattie Haskett Bell of\nLeon, Harry Johnson of Iowa City,\nRalph and Marie Lehter, of Cashmere,\nWashington, and two great grandchil\ndren, Edgar Haskett Bell and Jennie\nLester Bell, of I^eon. She united with\nthe Congregational church at Salem.\nApril 25, 1858, and with one except\nion was the oldest member, and re\nmained an earnest and devoted mem\nber of that church during her life\ntime. She was not simply a membei\nin name but in fact, and her good\nworks in the church will not soon be\nforgotten. She was a loving mother,\na kind neighbor, a loyal and true\nchristian, showing by her daily and\nconsistent life the faith that she pro\nfessed. Her presence was a gentle\nbenediction upon those around her.\nShe will be sadly missed in the home\ncircle and by her acquaintances. She\nhas lived to a good old age, her beau\ntiful life is past, but its influence\nwill be felt for years to come. She\nfias gone to join her loved ones in\nthat better world where there is no\nparting. She died as she had often\nwished, falling peacefully, sweetly\nasleep in Jesus, and as her children\nstood around her dying bed to watch\nthe last fleeting breath, the hovering\nangels opend wide the golden gates\nand a revered mother entered into\nrest. The funeral cortege left her\nlate home and wended its way to the\nCongregational church, where a largo\nconcourse of sorrowing friends had\ngathered at 2 o'clock Saturday after\nnoon. The funeral arrangements,\nmade by the deceased, were carried\nout. Rev W. T. Butcher conducted\nimpressive services. The floral of\nferings were many and beautiful,\nStation Agent A. J. Ingrim depart\ned Thursday for a trip to Colorado\nand Wyoming.\nFrank Hawkins, train dispatcher at\nHannibal, Mo., his wife and two sons.\nMerrill and Ralph, are guests at the\nparental home, Mr. and Mrs. j. W.\nHawkins.\nFollowing an extended visit with\nher cousin, Mrs. G. W. Barber, Miss\nNellie Lewis has returned to Reinbeck.\nMiss Cophine Rook is at home for\nthe summer vacation. She has been\nattending school at Cedar Falls.\nHon. Enoch Beery of Salem Is\nnominated for his third term, as rep\nresentative from this district.\nAfter visiting her friend, Mrs. Azur\nBurton, Mrs. Cramer has returned to\nBirmingham.\nMiss Bertha McKee came from\nMontgomery, Alabama, to visit her\nsister, Mrs W. Hoggatt.\nLittle Miss Anna Ingrim is visiting\nher aunt, Mrs. T. B. Sater, at Dan\nville.\nChildren's day services will bd held\nat- the Congregational church at 11\no'clock Sunday morning. At the M.\nK. church Sunday evening.\nMiss. Maude Whistler arrived home\nfrom Washington state Thursday.\nMrs. J. B. .Torden recently enter\ntained her mother, Mrs, Kate Cochran,\nfrom Hillsboro.\nMra. J. W. Rhode came from Keo\nkuk to fepend a few days with her\nparents. Mr. and Mrs. Peter Knight.\nMiss Mary Garretson is home from\nChicago to spend her vacation.\n-Miss Mertie Mitchell has returned\nWEDNESDAY,: JUNE 15, i9l\nKeep Your Eye on the\nBurlington's New Main Line\nThrough Central Wyoming\nthe riche-.t under eloped country in the west.\nThe Big Horn Basin\nis now so well started on its great wealth producing era that\nit not only appeals to farmers looking for new